The $\omega$ phase can be either \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_hP3_191_a_d-001}{hexagonal ($C32$)} or trigonal (shown here). The trigonal $\omega$ phase transforms into several high-symmetry structures under certain conditions: \begin{center} \begin{tabular}{ccc} ${\mathbf c/a}$ & ${\mathbf z}$ & \textbf{Lattice} \\ \hline Arbitrary & $\frac12$ & \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_hP3_191_a_d-001}{Ideal Omega ($C32$)} \\ $\sqrt{\frac38}$ & $\frac16$ & \href{current_web_home_dir/A_cI2_229_a-001}{Body-Centered Cubic ($A2$)} \\ $\sqrt{\frac32}$ & $\frac16$ & \href{current_web_home_dir/A_cP1_221_a-001}{Simple Cubic ($A_{h}$)} \\ $\sqrt{6}$ & $\frac16$ & \href{current_web_home_dir/A_cF4_225_a-001}{Face-Centered Cubic ($A1$)} \\ Arbitrary & 0 & \href{current_web_home_dir/A_hP1_191_a-001}{Simple Hexagonal Structure ($A_{f}$)} \end{tabular} \end{center} ~ \vspace{-.25in} 
 For more details about the omega phase and materials which form in the omega phase, see (Sikka, 1982) . As noted there, most omega phase intermetallic alloys are disordered. Although the ``$\omega$'' label comes from $\omega$-CrTi, (Ewald, 1931) lists the prototype for {\em Strukturbericht} designation $C6$ as CdI$_{2}$. 
 Alternative stackings for CdI$_{2}$ have been proposed, including \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_hP9_156_2ab_a2b3c-001}{a $6H$ stacking} and the \href{current_web_home_dir/AB2_hP6_186_b_ab-001}{questionable $C27$ structure}.
